1
00:00:53,510 --> 00:00:55,180
<i>The war between sorcerers</i>

2
00:00:55,220 --> 00:00:57,740
<i>was fought in the shadows of history</i>

3
00:00:57,850 --> 00:01:03,220
<i>and the fate of mankind rested with
the just and powerful Merlin.</i>

4
00:01:04,930 --> 00:01:08,380
<i>He taught his secrets
to three trusted apprentices,</i>

5
00:01:08,530 --> 00:01:12,830
<i>Balthazar, Veronica, and Horvath.</i>

6
00:01:13,770 --> 00:01:15,670
<i>He should have trusted only two.</i>

7
00:01:23,540 --> 00:01:25,910
<i>Veronica and Balthazar
witnessed the savagery</i>

8
00:01:25,950 --> 00:01:27,970
<i>of a sorcerer beyond evil,</i>

9
00:01:33,190 --> 00:01:37,450
<i>Morgana le Fay,
Merlin's most deadly enemy.</i>

10
00:01:54,440 --> 00:01:56,640
We are but servants.

11
00:01:58,650 --> 00:02:00,270
- Merlin.
- Horvath!

12
00:02:01,950 --> 00:02:03,310
You betray me?

13
00:02:06,520 --> 00:02:08,080
I am no one's servant.

14
00:02:10,590 --> 00:02:12,890
Well done. Now get the spell.

15
00:02:12,960 --> 00:02:17,920
<i>And so it was. Morgana
gained sorcery's most dangerous spell</i>

16
00:02:18,130 --> 00:02:20,460
<i>known as "The Rising, "</i>

17
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:23,660
<i>giving Morgana the power
to raise an army of the dead</i>

18
00:02:23,700 --> 00:02:25,040
<i>and enslave mankind.</i>

19
00:02:40,820 --> 00:02:43,810
<i>Veronica sacrificed herself
for Balthazar</i>

20
00:02:43,860 --> 00:02:47,160
<i>by drawing Morgana's soul
into her own body.</i>

21
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:50,660
<i>But Morgana began to kill her
from the inside.</i>

22
00:02:52,870 --> 00:02:56,390
<i>To save Veronica's life
and to capture Morgana,</i>

23
00:02:56,540 --> 00:02:59,870
<i>Balthazar trapped them both
in the Grimhold,</i>

24
00:03:00,340 --> 00:03:02,040
<i>an inescapable prison.</i>

25
00:03:04,180 --> 00:03:07,200
<i>Over time,
Balthazar fought many sorcerers</i>

26
00:03:07,250 --> 00:03:08,880
<i>who tried to free Morgana,</i>

27
00:03:09,020 --> 00:03:12,010
<i>trapping them in layer upon layer
of the doll.</i>

28
00:03:13,390 --> 00:03:16,250
<i>Eventually, he captured
Horvath as well.</i>

29
00:03:18,260 --> 00:03:22,090
<i>As Merlin lay dying,
he gave Balthazar his dragon ring,</i>

30
00:03:22,230 --> 00:03:24,660
<i>saying it would guide him to the child</i>

31
00:03:24,700 --> 00:03:27,760
<i>who would one day grow
to be Merlin's successor,</i>

32
00:03:28,140 --> 00:03:29,660
<i>the Prime Merlinean.</i>

33
00:03:29,870 --> 00:03:32,270
The Prime Merlinean is the only one

34
00:03:33,110 --> 00:03:35,580
who can kill Morgana.

35
00:03:35,710 --> 00:03:38,870
<i>Balthazar would search for centuries.</i>

36
00:03:54,860 --> 00:03:58,460
<i>And never, it is said,
will Balthazar waver from his quest,</i>

37
00:03:59,130 --> 00:04:01,430
<i>for mankind will never be safe</i>

38
00:04:01,570 --> 00:04:06,730
<i>until Morgana is destroyed
by the Prime Merlinean.</i>

39
00:04:16,350 --> 00:04:19,150
Hey, Tank.
How did you even get up here?

40
00:04:19,390 --> 00:04:21,880
David? Field trip today.

41
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:24,190
Don't forget to wear clean underwear.

42
00:04:24,230 --> 00:04:26,250
She means me, not you.

43
00:04:53,120 --> 00:04:55,150
You're not supposed to be
doing that, Dave.

44
00:04:56,260 --> 00:04:57,280
Now!

45
00:05:00,030 --> 00:05:01,050
David.

46
00:05:02,630 --> 00:05:04,000
That's cool.

47
00:05:17,980 --> 00:05:22,380
...which means that before Ellis Island
and the Statue of Liberty were built...

48
00:05:22,980 --> 00:05:24,470
Pass it to Becky.

49
00:05:24,620 --> 00:05:26,480
Pass it on.
Pass it on.

50
00:05:26,620 --> 00:05:28,560
- Pass it to Becky.
- Here.

51
00:05:47,210 --> 00:05:48,230
Let's go.

52
00:05:48,410 --> 00:05:51,400
Get on the ferry. Get your bags.
Stay close. Here we go.

53
00:06:01,890 --> 00:06:03,450
Hey, stop!

54
00:06:20,510 --> 00:06:22,170
Excuse me, excuse me.

55
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:23,910
No!

56
00:06:24,710 --> 00:06:25,770
No, lady, don't!

57
00:07:32,750 --> 00:07:33,840
No way.

58
00:07:47,030 --> 00:07:49,360
The second emperor
of the Han dynasty

59
00:07:49,500 --> 00:07:54,730
locked his least-favorite wife
in this urn for 10 years to the day.

60
00:07:55,770 --> 00:07:59,230
They say you open it up,
the same thing will happen to you.

61
00:08:00,170 --> 00:08:02,640
I'm sorry. I'm looking for this note.

62
00:08:02,680 --> 00:08:05,610
Have you seen it?
It kind of just blew into your store.

63
00:08:06,380 --> 00:08:07,510
A note?

64
00:08:07,650 --> 00:08:09,140
It blew into your store.

65
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:11,150
It was just a...

66
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:12,910
Coincidence.

67
00:08:13,050 --> 00:08:14,580
Yeah, it was just a coincidence.

68
00:08:20,630 --> 00:08:22,890
I have something
I'd like to show you, Dave.

69
00:08:23,030 --> 00:08:25,790
- How'd you know my name was Dave?
- 'Cause I can read minds!

70
00:08:28,540 --> 00:08:29,940
It's on your backpack.

71
00:08:33,410 --> 00:08:34,500
Come over here.

72
00:08:48,790 --> 00:08:50,920
This is very special

73
00:08:51,030 --> 00:08:53,960
and if it likes you, you can keep it.

74
00:08:55,230 --> 00:08:58,600
I better not. My teacher said
I couldn't be gone for long.

75
00:08:58,630 --> 00:08:59,830
She knows I'm here.

76
00:08:59,930 --> 00:09:01,400
You're a bad liar, Dave.

77
00:09:02,940 --> 00:09:04,400
That's good.

78
00:09:10,210 --> 00:09:11,640
Oh, boy.

79
00:09:38,970 --> 00:09:40,170
No way.

80
00:09:41,410 --> 00:09:45,640
I have been searching a very long time.

81
00:09:47,150 --> 00:09:50,240
Magically, here you are.

82
00:09:50,890 --> 00:09:53,550
That ring on your finger
means something, Dave.

83
00:09:54,590 --> 00:09:55,950
It means

84
00:09:55,990 --> 00:09:59,860
you're going to be
a very important sorcerer one day.

85
00:10:00,630 --> 00:10:05,570
And your first lesson begins right now
with your very own Encantus.

86
00:10:06,430 --> 00:10:09,770
Do not move, do not touch anything.

87
00:11:10,160 --> 00:11:11,500
No way.

88
00:11:30,850 --> 00:11:32,080
When am I?

89
00:11:32,650 --> 00:11:34,090
New York City.

90
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:37,890
Not where. The year.

91
00:11:38,830 --> 00:11:41,690
You are wasting my time.

92
00:11:47,230 --> 00:11:50,970
What happened
to "don't touch anything"?

93
00:11:51,110 --> 00:11:53,160
That's not very sporting of you,
Balthazar.

94
00:11:53,210 --> 00:11:54,230
Be quiet.

95
00:11:54,710 --> 00:11:58,440
It's not you. He's been like this
for 1,000 years. I'll explain later.

96
00:11:59,210 --> 00:12:01,340
I need the Grimhold. Where's that doll?

97
00:12:44,060 --> 00:12:45,360
I'll have that doll.

98
00:13:32,770 --> 00:13:34,800
I want that doll.

99
00:13:42,180 --> 00:13:44,150
Leave, Dave! Leave now!

100
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:56,790
David Stutler! Don't ever leave your...

101
00:13:56,830 --> 00:13:58,660
There's these crazy wizard guys
in there!

102
00:13:58,700 --> 00:13:59,890
They're made of roaches!

103
00:14:00,300 --> 00:14:03,740
No! Don't go in there!
The store's on fire! Don't go in!

104
00:14:03,870 --> 00:14:05,570
Those guys are

105
00:14:08,810 --> 00:14:09,830
crazy.

106
00:14:14,250 --> 00:14:16,510
You really shouldn't
tell stories. Let's go.

107
00:14:19,490 --> 00:14:21,220
Ew! He peed his pants!

108
00:14:24,190 --> 00:14:27,960
A jar broke. It's just water!
There was a fire!

109
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:32,490
Yeah, Stutler had a leak.

110
00:14:33,130 --> 00:14:34,530
He's such a geek.

111
00:15:04,930 --> 00:15:06,990
Good morning. What is that? Oh, right.

112
00:15:08,870 --> 00:15:11,030
Good morning, beautiful.

113
00:15:14,980 --> 00:15:16,100
Hey, heads up.

114
00:15:16,210 --> 00:15:17,270
Oh.

115
00:15:17,310 --> 00:15:18,510
Happy birthday.

116
00:15:19,280 --> 00:15:20,640
Thank you, Bennet.

117
00:15:21,650 --> 00:15:23,010
You're up early.

118
00:15:23,720 --> 00:15:29,020
Professor Heiderman wants me to give
a presentation to his Physics 101 class.

119
00:15:29,160 --> 00:15:31,320
What? Teaching long division
to English majors?

120
00:15:31,460 --> 00:15:34,290
I know. It's like the Peace Corps,
but it's Heiderman's class.

121
00:15:34,330 --> 00:15:37,700
Hey, Bio nerds
are getting drunk tonight.

122
00:15:40,100 --> 00:15:42,760
And we invited cheerleaders
from Princeton.

123
00:15:43,040 --> 00:15:45,440
Oh. So there's smart cheerleaders.

124
00:15:46,570 --> 00:15:50,910
So, seriously, you're saying you don't
want to go out on your birthday?

125
00:15:52,750 --> 00:15:56,270
I got to finish my Tesla coil project
if I want to graduate.

126
00:15:58,690 --> 00:16:02,280
Dave, are you familiar
with the gray wolf?

127
00:16:02,420 --> 00:16:05,520
Oh, no, please, Bennet. Not this again
with the gray wolf. I can't...

128
00:16:05,560 --> 00:16:07,990
The gray wolf is a pack animal.

129
00:16:08,500 --> 00:16:12,830
He must find a mate.
He must hunt and grunt.

130
00:16:12,870 --> 00:16:14,630
He must participate.

131
00:16:14,770 --> 00:16:17,000
You're going to get
booted out of the pack!

132
00:16:17,140 --> 00:16:20,400
Alone. Eaten by a hungry bear.

133
00:16:21,040 --> 00:16:26,210
That's a real pick-me-up pep talk,
and I'm ready to go get the day.

134
00:16:33,890 --> 00:16:35,790
No, no.

135
00:16:36,090 --> 00:16:37,720
Oh, man.

136
00:16:41,760 --> 00:16:43,630
Everything okay down there?

137
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:51,170
I should just leave, right?

138
00:16:51,670 --> 00:16:52,700
Right.

139
00:17:02,250 --> 00:17:05,220
Wait. I'm sorry. Becky?

140
00:17:05,650 --> 00:17:07,140
Becky Barnes.

141
00:17:10,960 --> 00:17:12,750
Dave!

142
00:17:14,630 --> 00:17:16,360
We were in fourth grade together.

143
00:17:16,860 --> 00:17:19,130
I do know you. Dave Stutler.

144
00:17:19,170 --> 00:17:20,860
- Right?
- That's me.

145
00:17:21,840 --> 00:17:23,430
Yeah. You're that kid.

146
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:25,040
What was that place called?

147
00:17:25,070 --> 00:17:27,230
- Arcana...
- Arcana Cabana?

148
00:17:27,570 --> 00:17:28,700
Yeah.

149
00:17:29,840 --> 00:17:32,680
- So, did you transfer?
- Yeah, I did.

150
00:17:32,880 --> 00:17:36,510
And got some help. Treatment.

151
00:17:36,720 --> 00:17:39,410
Yes, that was weird.

152
00:17:39,650 --> 00:17:43,420
You know what? It turns out
it's just a glucose imbalance.

153
00:17:43,760 --> 00:17:45,020
Hallucinations?

154
00:17:45,130 --> 00:17:47,990
- Not uncommon in young subjects.
- Ah...

155
00:17:48,500 --> 00:17:49,690
Right.

156
00:17:50,030 --> 00:17:52,260
It's a great anecdote.

157
00:18:11,250 --> 00:18:12,620
Hey, Becky.

158
00:18:13,920 --> 00:18:15,980
Becky? Hey, Becky?

159
00:18:16,520 --> 00:18:19,790
So how are you enjoying Physics 101?

160
00:18:20,030 --> 00:18:23,020
My brain
just does not think physics.

161
00:18:23,300 --> 00:18:25,130
So, what does it think, then?

162
00:18:25,170 --> 00:18:26,960
Music, mostly.

163
00:18:27,800 --> 00:18:29,670
So, this is me.

164
00:18:29,870 --> 00:18:31,600
You work at the radio station?

165
00:18:32,270 --> 00:18:34,640
Yeah, I do an afternoon show.

166
00:18:34,670 --> 00:18:36,540
Are you kidding me? That's so cool!

167
00:18:36,580 --> 00:18:40,600
It's just college radio.
Like, seven people listen to it.

168
00:18:41,080 --> 00:18:43,740
I'll be listening. That's one more.
You can round it up to eight.

169
00:18:47,750 --> 00:18:49,920
I think that's our antenna!

170
00:18:50,490 --> 00:18:51,920
- What's going on?
Hey, gorgeous.

171
00:18:51,960 --> 00:18:55,620
The whole mixer is toast,
and Freddy called in sick.

172
00:18:58,030 --> 00:18:59,460
Sorry to bother you.

173
00:18:59,500 --> 00:19:02,130
Where does your engineer
keep his equipment?

174
00:19:02,870 --> 00:19:04,030
Who's this guy?

175
00:19:05,370 --> 00:19:08,000
So, the good news is
you're still transmitting.

176
00:19:08,040 --> 00:19:11,570
The bad news is
your return loss, way too high.

177
00:19:15,880 --> 00:19:18,110
All right, if I know what I'm doing,

178
00:19:18,450 --> 00:19:22,650
we should be good!

179
00:19:25,430 --> 00:19:26,520
Yes!

180
00:19:28,090 --> 00:19:30,560
- Thank you.
- No, please, it was my pleasure.

181
00:19:31,030 --> 00:19:34,000
I could tell
this is all pretty important for you.

182
00:19:34,500 --> 00:19:39,370
My show is the one thing that...
Well, you know.

183
00:19:39,440 --> 00:19:40,630
Mmm-hmm.

184
00:19:42,180 --> 00:19:44,700
Physics. That's my thing.

185
00:19:56,820 --> 00:19:58,290
I'll see you around.

186
00:19:58,430 --> 00:20:00,220
You didn't ask her out!

187
00:20:00,290 --> 00:20:02,160
You just fixed her antenna and you left.

188
00:20:02,200 --> 00:20:06,560
That's not the point.
She will remember me.

189
00:20:06,800 --> 00:20:09,960
"She will remember me"?
Who are you? Braveheart?

190
00:20:10,070 --> 00:20:13,400
Bennet, I blew my shot
at getting this girl 10 years ago.

191
00:20:13,440 --> 00:20:15,070
I can't do it again.

192
00:20:15,510 --> 00:20:18,070
Now get out of here
before you get electrocuted.

193
00:20:19,680 --> 00:20:21,840
<i>...and it's
a miracle we made it on the air tonight.</i>

194
00:20:21,950 --> 00:20:24,750
<i>This show may not matter,
but the music does.</i>

195
00:20:24,780 --> 00:20:29,280
<i>This is Becky Barnes, WN YU Radio,
hoping there's music all around you.</i>

196
00:21:03,720 --> 00:21:07,720
I don't understand. Why did you have
to buy this piece of junk?

197
00:21:07,760 --> 00:21:10,200
Junk? It's an antique!

198
00:21:10,260 --> 00:21:13,490
Antique? It's a piece of junk
from a flea market!

199
00:21:30,280 --> 00:21:32,220
Am I the first one out?

200
00:21:35,060 --> 00:21:36,320
That's a yes.

201
00:21:36,520 --> 00:21:39,080
Our 10 years are up, Balthazar.

202
00:21:40,260 --> 00:21:42,460
When I get the Grimhold
from young David,

203
00:21:42,500 --> 00:21:44,360
I'll tell him you said hello.

204
00:21:46,570 --> 00:21:48,560
Cheerio, Balthazar!

205
00:22:44,220 --> 00:22:46,560
I thought B- was generous.

206
00:22:46,860 --> 00:22:49,760
I've recently been released
from a 10-year sentence,

207
00:22:49,800 --> 00:22:52,660
during which the only reading material
available to me

208
00:22:52,800 --> 00:22:56,530
was your so-called report
on Napoleon Bonaparte

209
00:22:56,570 --> 00:22:58,230
from your school bag.

210
00:22:58,540 --> 00:23:00,530
Your analysis was obvious,
your prose was weak.

211
00:23:00,870 --> 00:23:02,970
- I was nine.
- Irrelevant.

212
00:23:03,540 --> 00:23:07,100
Where's the Grimhold?
That doll you took from the shop.

213
00:23:07,410 --> 00:23:10,080
The doll held something very powerful.

214
00:23:10,120 --> 00:23:12,680
Something very important to me.

215
00:23:12,950 --> 00:23:14,820
You had it last.

216
00:23:14,850 --> 00:23:16,250
I want it back.

217
00:23:16,320 --> 00:23:17,790
Listen, I'm...

218
00:23:18,660 --> 00:23:21,090
- I threw it in the street.
- Where's the Grimhold?

219
00:23:21,130 --> 00:23:23,320
It's been a long time.
I don't actually know where it is.

220
00:23:26,170 --> 00:23:28,930
I'll cut the truth out of you.

221
00:23:36,980 --> 00:23:38,030
Sweet.

222
00:23:41,350 --> 00:23:42,610
Get him.

223
00:23:44,250 --> 00:23:46,380
Wolves? No, no, no, no.

224
00:23:54,760 --> 00:23:55,820
Oh!

225
00:24:03,170 --> 00:24:04,260
Thank you.

226
00:24:07,540 --> 00:24:08,730
Wolves.

227
00:24:21,790 --> 00:24:24,350
Man, oh, man, oh, man, oh, man.

228
00:24:28,660 --> 00:24:30,290
No, no, no.

229
00:24:31,360 --> 00:24:32,660
Oh, no!

230
00:24:36,600 --> 00:24:38,000
Kill him.

231
00:24:38,770 --> 00:24:40,210
No!

232
00:24:44,040 --> 00:24:45,270
Puppies?

233
00:24:51,750 --> 00:24:52,810
Oh, my.

234
00:24:55,320 --> 00:24:56,550
No way.

235
00:24:57,390 --> 00:24:59,050
Where's the doll, Dave?

236
00:25:00,160 --> 00:25:01,460
Him, him.

237
00:25:05,830 --> 00:25:07,860
All right, get up here.
Now! Now! Hurry!

238
00:25:18,850 --> 00:25:19,900
Oh, no!

239
00:25:41,970 --> 00:25:44,770
This is not happening.
This is not happening.

240
00:25:44,800 --> 00:25:46,360
I taste sour in my mouth.

241
00:25:46,540 --> 00:25:48,730
Take it easy, Dave. Deep breaths.

242
00:25:53,680 --> 00:25:54,700
What?

243
00:25:56,620 --> 00:25:58,550
Now that is not happening!

244
00:25:58,590 --> 00:26:00,610
What's wrong?
What is it?

245
00:26:01,250 --> 00:26:03,050
No, no, no, no!

246
00:26:03,090 --> 00:26:05,180
You are not doing this to me again!

247
00:26:05,930 --> 00:26:09,760
Do you have any idea what my life
has been like for the last 10 years?

248
00:26:09,800 --> 00:26:11,890
I've been stuck in an urn
for the last 10 years.

249
00:26:12,830 --> 00:26:17,170
So have I! A figurative urn of ridicule.

250
00:26:18,100 --> 00:26:21,160
Do you know that in certain parts
of the tri-state area,

251
00:26:21,210 --> 00:26:24,040
they still refer
to having a nervous breakdown

252
00:26:24,080 --> 00:26:27,340
as "pulling a David Stutler"?
Did you know that?

253
00:26:27,410 --> 00:26:28,850
Try to be a good listener, Dave.

254
00:26:30,280 --> 00:26:32,380
That doll is called the Grimhold.

255
